    <Set guid="5FF59592-D562-404F-87C0-B02D5228A525" name="Solutions">
      <Description>Definition A solution (or design artifact / solution type) is an abstractly described construct, model, method, or architecture that embodies a deliberate design response to one or more identified challenges and is intended to satisfy specified requirements. It represents how challenges may be addressed, without being bound to a single instantiation or context. Inclusion criteria: •The contribution is explicitly positioned as a response to one or more challenges. •The solution operationalizes requirements through a recognizable design construct. •The description goes beyond problem articulation and specifies a means of addressing it. •The solution is abstracted beyond a single case, implementation, or organization. •The solution can be categorized as a design artifact, such as: •a conceptual or semantic model, •a framework or reference architecture, •a method or procedure, •a governance or coordination mechanism, •a combination of these. Exclusion criteria: •Problem descriptions or challenges without a proposed means of resolution. •Normative requirements stated without an accompanying design response. •Purely technical implementations or tools described without abstraction. •Empirical observations of practice that do not articulate a design contribution. •Outcomes, impacts, or performance results without specification of the underlying artifact.</Description>
